Problem Statement¶

Are multi-disciplined professional cyclists more successful than single discipline cyclists?¶

UCI cycling data is generally difficult to acquire, especially for projects such as this one. Luckily I have managed to track down two of the cleaner datasets that are available. However the data is more complete for the male riders than the female rider as a result of this, I will remove the female related data.

1. Gather data¶

The first file¶

Dataset 1¶

Type: .csv file

Method: This .csv was downloaded directly from: https://data.mendeley.com/datasets/mkzht8948x/2

Dataset variables:

Breakdown¶

'sport' is broken down by 8 overall categories: 'mountain-bike', 'trials', 'bmx-freestyle', 'bmx-racing', 'indoor', 'cyclo-cross', 'road' and 'track'

'discipline' are sub-categories of 'sport': 'Cross-country short circuit', 'Cross-country Olympic', 'Enduro', 'Downhill', 'Cross-country marathon', 'Cross-country eliminator', 'E-MTB Enduro', '4X', '20-inch Wheel Size', '26-inch Wheel Size', 'Open', 'E-MTB Cross-country', 'Cross-country team relay', 'Pump Track', 'Cross-country Olympic Junior Series', 'E-MTB Cross-Country Marathon', 'Park', 'Flatland', 'Individual', 'Artistic Cycling ACT4', 'Pair Artistic Cycling Women', 'Pair Artistic Cycling Mix', 'Single Artistic Cycling Men', 'Single Artistic Cycling Women', 'Cycle-ball', 'Individual Road Race', 'Individual Time Trial', 'Team Time Trial', 'Individual Pursuit', 'Keirin', 'Time Trial', 'Team Sprint', 'Scratch', 'Sprint', 'Team Pursuit', 'Madison', 'Omnium', 'Points Race', 'Elimination Race', 'Cross-country marathon Series', 'Cross-country stage races', 'Cross-country point-to-point', 'Team time trial mixed relay' and 'Olympic Sprint'

'classification' contains codes that are used by the UCI to describe the races, some are somewhat self-explanatory, e.g. '1.WWT - 1 day - UCI Women’s WorldTour' while others would require some knowledge and pairing with other column values e.g. 'CL3 - Class 3'. For this analysis we won’t need this column

‘competition’ contains the actual names of the races e.g. Tour de France, UCI BMX Supercross World Cup etc.

‘location’ contains an abbreviated code for the host nation for each race. E.g. ITA, FRA, GBR etc.

‘jr_u23_elite_masters’ references the age categories for each race:

‘Elite’, ‘Junior’, ‘Masters’ and ‘Under 23’ We will focus on the ‘Elites’ groups, as these are more representative of the current professional roster

‘year’ is the year of each race

‘class_code’ is a UCI code system that works as an numerical identifier for the 'classification' column

‘rank’ is the position the rider finished in the race

‘fullname’ is the full name of each rider

‘last_name’ is the surname of each rider

‘first_name’ is the first name of each rider

‘country’ contains an abbreviated code for rider. E.g. ITA, FRA, GBR etc.

‘team’ the team names, were applicable, for each rider. Note:- Team names can change over time, especially in terms of sponsorship. E.g. ‘Lotto NL Jumbo’ became ‘JUMBO-VISMA’

‘gender’ is split between ‘F’ and ‘M’

‘age’ is the age of each rider

‘result’ contains the finishing time information for each race/stage

'points' refer to the number of UCI points earned per stage/race that impact the riders world ranking

The Second File¶

Dataset 2¶

Type: .csv

Method: Programatically from Kaggle. Username and API "Kaggle Key is required"

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fewinder/uci-pro-road-cycling-dataset

The second file contains more, what could be described as 'bio' and team data for the riders

Dataset variables:

Year - The year that the rider was with their team

Function - This refers to the role that the rider would hold im this particular datasets Note: there is only one role "Rider. However this is more nuanced as rider could have many other roles in the team, "Team Leader" or "Domesituqe" (helper), however this dataset does not contain this information.

Last Name - The riders surname

First Name - The riders first name

Birth date - The riders date of birth in the international format - d/m/y

Birth date US - The riders date of birth in the US format - m/d/y

Age - The riders age at the time of the creation of this dataset

Gender - The riders given gender at the time of the creation of this dataset

Category - This is abbreviated description of each riders team, usually split between WTT (World Tour Team) and a variations of "Continental Teams", sometimes split by gender: CTM - Continental Team Men, CTM - Continental Team Women

Country - The country that the rider is from

Continent - The continent that the rider is from

Team Code - This is abbreviated description of each riders team name

Team Name - The full version of the team name

UCIID - The ID given to each rider by the governing body: Union Cycliste Internationale (UCI)

2. Assess data¶

Assess the data according to data quality and tidiness metrics using the report below.

List two data quality issues and two tidiness issues. Assess each data issue visually and programmatically, then briefly describe the issue you find. Make sure you include justifications for the methods you use for the assessment.

Tidiness Issue for the 1st file:¶

There is an issue with some of the race names, in particular the "Grand Tour" (La Vuelta ciclista a España) and the multi-stage races 'Paris-Nice' and 'Tirreno-Adriatico'

The Spanish grand tour (La Vuelta ciclista a España) was once called "Vuelta a España", both names have been recorded in this dataset, it gives the impression that they are two different races.

The function below will produce a visualization of the problem

Function depository¶

In [73]:
def mens_races_by_location(location):
    """
    Plots the number of races for a given location where classification is '2.UWT - Stages - UCI WorldTour'.
    
    Parameters:
    location (str): The location to filter the races (e.g., 'ESP', 'ITA', 'GBR').
    """
    # Filter the data for the specific conditions
    filtered_df = df1[(df1['location'] == location) & (df1['classification'] == '2.UWT - Stages - UCI WorldTour')]

    # Count the number of races per competition
    competition_counts = filtered_df['competition'].value_counts()

    # Create a bar chart
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    competition_counts.plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue')
    plt.title(f'Number of Races in {location} with Classification 2.UWT - Stages - UCI WorldTour')
    plt.xlabel('Competition')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Races')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

Quality issue - File 1¶

Given that the dataset contains different cycling disciplines, the 'result' column will have a mixture of times (recorded in different formats e.g. "+5.00") 'DSQ' (Disqualified), 'DNF' (Did Not Finish), 'DNS' (Did Not Start) 'LAP' and NaN.

The name of the column 'result' may or may not cause confusion because it refers to the time (in some cases) result of the race/stage. Whereas 'rank' refers to the overall position that the rider finished, 1st, 32nd etc. This means that any single rider can have multiple entries, but not actually duplicates

Using the graph below, we can see how this mixture of results will impact validity of the analysis

Quality Resolutions for the first file¶

Issues and justification: FILL IN

Since this analysis will look at the success of multi-disciplined riders who also participate in road races vs those who participate solely in road racing I will:

Remove the "result" column as this has too many inconsistent variables as seen below

Keep the "DNS"/"DNF"/"DSQ", as this may assist in the overall analysis

Rename the 'rank' column but keep the data as it will be vital to the overall analysis. This will make it more understandable to the reader

Convert the dataset to one row per rider, thus removing multiple entries

Drop "age" column as I can use the more accurate birth date from the second file

Keeping things simple for df1¶

To make things as clear as possible, I will split the races into the following columns

Giro d'Italia

Tour de France

La Vuelta ciclista a España

Stage Races

One-Day Races

National Championship Race

National Championship Time Trail

Continental Championship Race

Continental Championship Time Trail

World Championship Race

World Championship Time Trail

Olympic Road Race

Olmypic Time Trail

Furthermore: each of the race column will show a count of how many times each rider finished on the podium (1st, 2nd or 3rd), else 0

The gender column dataype will be changed to category for speed

Where applicable. the number of road, mountain bike, cyclocross, indoor and track will be counted for each rider

Finally, the number of DNS (Did Not Start), DNF (Did Not Finish) and DSQ (Disqualified) will be counted for each rider

# FILL IN - Apply the cleaning strategy


# Creating helper columns for counting
df1['one_day_race'] = ((df1['classification'] == '1.UWT - 1 day - UCI WorldTour') & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1["giro_d'italia"] = ((df1['competition'].str.contains("Giro d'Italia", case=False, na=False)) & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1["tour_de_france"] = ((df1['competition'].str.contains("Tour de France", case=False, na=False)) & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1["la_vuelta_ciclista_a_españa"] = ((df1['competition'].str.contains("La Vuelta ciclista a España", case=False, na=False)) & 
                                      (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)

# Creating a helper column for stage races
df1['stage_races'] = ((df1['classification'] == '2.UWT - Stages - UCI WorldTour') &
                      (~df1['competition'].str.contains("Giro d'Italia|Tour de France|La Vuelta ciclista a España", 
                                                        case=False, na=False)) &
                      (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)

# Creating binary columns for sports
df1['mountain_bike'] = (df1['sport'] == 'mountain-bike').astype(int)
df1['cyclo_cross'] = (df1['sport'] == 'cyclo-cross').astype(int)
df1['indoor'] = (df1['sport'] == 'indoor').astype(int)
df1['track'] = (df1['sport'] == 'track').astype(int)
df1['road'] = (df1['sport'] == 'road').astype(int)


# Creating columns that represent the riders current and former age classifications
df1['junior'] = df1['jr_u23_elite_masters'].str.contains('Junior', case=False, na=False)
df1['u_23'] = df1['jr_u23_elite_masters'].str.contains('U23', case=False, na=False)
df1['elite'] = df1['jr_u23_elite_masters'].str.contains('Elite', case=False, na=False)
df1['masters'] = df1['jr_u23_elite_masters'].str.contains('Masters', case=False, na=False)





# Creating columns that count the number of podium places for each competition
df1['individual_time_trial'] = ((df1['discipline'] == 'Individual Time Trial') & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1['team_time_trial'] = ((df1['discipline'] == 'Team Time Trial') & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1['team_time_trial_mixed_relay'] = ((df1['discipline'] == 'Team time trial mixed relay') & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1['olympic'] = (df1['competition'].str.contains('Olympic', case=False, na=False) & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1['world_championships'] = ((df1['classification'] == 'CM - UCI World Championships') & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1['continental_championships'] = ((df1['classification'] == 'CC - Continental Championships') & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)
df1['national_championships'] = ((df1['classification'] == 'CN - National Championships') & (df1['rank'].isin([1, 2, 3]))).astype(int)

# Creating columns that count the number of races not finished/started/disqualified
df1['DSQ'] = (df1['result'] == 'DSQ').astype(int)
df1['DNF'] = (df1['result'] == 'DNF').astype(int)
df1['DNS'] = (df1['result'] == 'DNS').astype(int)

# Grouping by fullname and aggregations
df1_cleaned = df1.groupby(['fullname', 'first_name', 'last_name', 'country', 'gender']).agg(

4. Update your data store¶

Update your local database/data store with the cleaned data, following best practices for storing your cleaned data:

  • Must maintain different instances / versions of data (raw and cleaned data)
  • Must name the dataset files informatively
  • Ensure both the raw and cleaned data is saved to your database/data store

The short version of the requirement is: Save a copy of your cleaned data (use a different name for the file so that you do not over-write the original) in the same location as the original data (usually the folder that contains the notebook).

Research question: FILL IN from answer to Step 1

5.1: Are multi-disciplined professional cyclists more successful the single discipline cyclists?¶

We will take a look at two grouped race types, "Road" (can be Grand Tours, multi-stage, One Day, Championship) and Time Trials – often called the “Race of Truth”, in cycling this type of race pits each rider against the clock. Whoever crosses the line with the fastest time wins (a full breakdown can be found here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Individual_time_trial). And will try to find out which party has had more success; this is measured by the number of podium places.

In [118]:
# Importing the data
In [119]:

df = data.drop(columns=['Unnamed: 0']).copy()
In [120]:
columns_to_check = ['cyclo_cross', 'mountain_bike', 'indoor', 'track']
single_disp = df.loc[~df[columns_to_check].any(axis=1)]
multi_disp = df.loc[df[columns_to_check].any(axis=1)]

assert set(single_disp.index).isdisjoint(set(multi_disp.index))

The above code breaks the data into the two aforementioned parties, Single Discipline and Multi-Discipline

combined_totals[['type','giro_d_italia', 'tour_de_france','la_vuelta_ciclista_a_españa'
                              ]].groupby(['type','giro_d_italia','tour_de_france', 'la_vuelta_ciclista_a_españa']).sum()

grand_tours = combined_totals[['type','giro_d_italia', 'tour_de_france','la_vuelta_ciclista_a_españa'
                              ]].groupby(['type','giro_d_italia','tour_de_france', 'la_vuelta_ciclista_a_españa']).sum().reset_index()

stage_races = combined_totals[['type','stage_races'
                              ]].groupby(['type','stage_races']).sum().reset_index()

                              ]].groupby(['type','one_day_race']).sum().reset_index()

championship_races = combined_totals[['type','olympic', 'world_championships','continental_championships', 'national_championships'
                              ]].groupby(['type','olympic', 'world_championships','continental_championships', 'national_championships']).sum().reset_index()

time_trail = combined_totals[['type','individual_time_trial', 'team_time_trial','team_time_trial_mixed_relay'
                             ]].groupby(['type','individual_time_trial', 'team_time_trial','team_time_trial_mixed_relay']
                                       ).sum().reset_index()


# Create the 'total_podium_places' column for each category
grand_tours['total_podium_places'] = grand_tours[['giro_d_italia', 'tour_de_france', 'la_vuelta_ciclista_a_españa']].sum(axis=1)
one_day_races['total_podium_places'] = one_day_races['one_day_race']

championship_races['total_podium_places'] = championship_races[['olympic', 'world_championships', 
                                                                'continental_championships', 'national_championships']].sum(axis=1)
time_trail['total_podium_places'] = time_trail[['individual_time_trial', 'team_time_trial','team_time_trial_mixed_relay']].sum(axis=1)


# Group by 'type' and sum the 'total_podium_places'
grand_tour_totals = grand_tours.groupby('type')['total_podium_places'].sum()
one_day_race_totals = one_day_races.groupby('type')['total_podium_places'].sum()
stage_race_totals = stage_races.groupby('type')['total_podium_places'].sum()
championship_race_totals = championship_races.groupby('type')['total_podium_places'].sum()
time_trail_totals = time_trail.groupby('type')['total_podium_places'].sum()

overall_results = pd.DataFrame({
 'Category': ['Grand Tours', 'One Day Races', 'Stage Races', 'Championship Races', 'Time Trails'],
    'Multi': [grand_tour_totals['Multi'], one_day_race_totals['Multi'], stage_race_totals['Multi'], championship_race_totals['Multi'], time_trail_totals['Multi']],
    'Single': [grand_tour_totals['Single'], one_day_race_totals['Single'], stage_race_totals['Single'], championship_race_totals['Single'], time_trail_totals['Single']]

})

plt.xlabel('Race Category')
plt.legend(title='Type')
plt.show();

5.2: Reflection¶

In 2-4 sentences, if you had more time to complete the project, what actions would you take? For example, which data quality and structural issues would you look into further, and what research questions would you further explore?

Answer: FILL IN These datasets are missing a lot of data, unfortunately (as mentioned) UCI datasets are rare and hard to find, especially when it comes to women’s racing. I would like to have reached out to the UCI for more information about the riders/results/competition. The website Pro Cycling Stats: https://www.procyclingstats.com/index.php does have much more comprehensive data, however while I can scrape the race data, it’s not centralised. For example, all of the races are on separate pages depending on the year, coupled with the fact that each rider also has their own page. It would take a considerable amount of time to collate all of the necessary data to complete this task.
It would’ve been interesting to see if there’s a difference in terms of single/multi disciplined male and female pro cyclists’ results However as an avid cycling fan I might take this on as a personal project.
